**Summary:** After scanning all 60 chapters of Diwan-E-Zauq, the best match for the question is chapter 5's maqta/title couplet. The original Urdu is: **"Ae Zauq waqt naale ke rakh le jigar pe haath / Warna jigar ko roye-ga tu dhar ke sar pe haath"** — "O Zauq, at the moment of complaint, keep your hand upon your heart / Or else you will weep for it, hands raised in grief." The classical Urdu poetic logic holds that the breath (dam) of the naala (lament/complaint) burns the jigar (heart/liver) like a flame — hence the instruction to hold one's hand over the jigar during the naala. Note that the search index does not cover Diwan-e-Zauq's English translations, so no chapter was found via keyword search; all 60 chapters were read directly.
